      <!-- Foundations -->
      <section id="foundations" class="section apo-block" data-tags="scripture logic history" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/CreativeWork">
        <h3>1) Foundations of Israelite Apologetics</h3>
        <p><strong>Definition.</strong> In Scripture, <em>apologia</em> is a reasoned defense (<span class="verse" data-ref="1 Peter 3:15" data-note="Be ready to give an answer (apologia) with meekness and fear.">1 Peter 3:15</span>). We defend by appealing to God’s truth, not to rhetoric alone.</p>
        <p><strong>Why identity matters.</strong> Identity is covenantal: promises, curses, and restoration are given to a people (<span class="verse" data-ref="Deuteronomy 7:6" data-note="A holy people unto the LORD, chosen.">Deuteronomy 7:6</span>).</p>
        <p><strong>Method.</strong> Scripture → Logic → History. We read the text, reason consistently, and test claims against evidence and context.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- Defending Identity -->
      <section id="defending-identity" class="section apo-block" data-tags="scripture history">
        <h3>2) Defending Israelite Identity</h3>
        <p><strong>Scripture:</strong> covenant markers and prophecies that identify Israel in history:
          <span class="verse" data-ref="Deuteronomy 28" data-note="Covenant blessings and curses as historical markers.">Deuteronomy 28</span>,
          <span class="verse" data-ref="Amos 9:7" data-note="Israel’s relation among nations (Ethiopia/Cush).">Amos 9:7</span>,
          <span class="verse" data-ref="Song of Songs 1:5–6" data-note="“I am black and lovely… the sun has looked upon me.”">Song of Songs 1:5–6</span>,
          <span class="verse" data-ref="Lamentations 5:10" data-note="Our skin was black like an oven because of the terrible famine.">Lamentations 5:10</span>.
        </p>
        <p><strong>History:</strong> Israelite historians, Arab writers, secular chroniclers, and slave trade records cross-reference the Scriptural picture.</p>
        <p><strong>Genealogy &amp; Diaspora:</strong> Migration patterns from Africa to the Americas and beyond, read alongside biblical geography and language.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- Objections / Fallacies -->
      <section id="objections" class="section apo-block" data-tags="fallacies scripture logic">
        <h3>3) Answering Common Fallacies (Objections)</h3>
        <div class="search-box" role="search">
          <input id="objection-search" type="search" placeholder="Enter an objection… (e.g., 'Skin color doesn’t matter')" aria-label="Search objections">
        </div>
        <div id="objection-list" aria-live="polite" style="margin-top:10px;">
          <details class="apg-acc" data-tags="skin color identity scripture">
            <summary>“Skin color doesn’t matter.”</summary>
            <p><strong>Logic:</strong> Distinguish moral worth (equal) from historical description (relevant). The objection confuses categories.</p>
            <p><strong>Scripture:</strong> The text names complexion and peoples as part of history, not superiority (<span class="verse" data-ref="Jeremiah 13:23" data-note="Can the Ethiopian change his skin?">Jeremiah 13:23</span>; <span class="verse" data-ref="Song of Songs 1:5–6" data-note="I am black and lovely.">Song of Songs 1:5–6</span>).</p>
            <p><strong>Context:</strong> Recognizing historic identity corrects later distortions and restores accurate reading.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="apg-acc" data-tags="proof identity black israelites evidence scripture history">
            <summary>“You can’t prove Israelites were Black.”</summary>
            <p><strong>Logic:</strong> Burden of proof is shared: weigh primary sources, not modern assumptions.</p>
            <p><strong>Scripture:</strong> Geographic and descriptive markers locate Israel amid Afro-Semitic peoples (<span class="verse" data-ref="Amos 9:7" data-note="Comparison with Cush/Ethiopia.">Amos 9:7</span>).</p>
            <p><strong>History:</strong> Iconography, travelers, and lexicons record dark-skinned populations across Israel’s sphere.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="apg-acc" data-tags="theology replacement covenant israel church supersessionism">
            <summary>“Christianity replaces Israelites.”</summary>
            <p><strong>Logic:</strong> Replacement claims invert covenant continuity.</p>
            <p><strong>Scripture:</strong> The promises and covenants remain identified with Israel and the grafted-in (<span class="verse" data-ref="Romans 11:1–2" data-note="Has God cast away His people? God forbid.">Romans 11:1–2</span>).</p>
          </details>

          <details class="apg-acc" data-tags="jewish people israel today identity comparison evidence">
            <summary>“The Jewish people in Israel today are the true Jews.”</summary>
            <p><strong>Logic:</strong> Present possession ≠ original identity; investigate sources rather than assume.</p>
            <p><strong>Scripture:</strong> Identity is tested by covenant signs and prophecy, not modern geopolitics (<span class="verse" data-ref="Deuteronomy 28" data-note="Covenant markers across history.">Deuteronomy 28</span>).</p>
            <p><strong>Context:</strong> This page assembles evidence rather than making ad hominem claims.</p>
          </details>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Logic Tools -->
      <section id="logic-tools" class="section apo-block" data-tags="logic">
        <h3>4) Tools of Logic</h3>
        <p>Mini-lessons and short videos on critical reasoning for Israelite apologetics.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Straw man:</strong> misrepresenting a position to refute an easier target (<span class="verse" data-ref="Matthew 4:6–7" data-note="Selective quotation vs. context; Yahusha answers with Scripture.">Matthew 4:6–7</span>).</li>
          <li><strong>Ad hominem:</strong> attacking the person rather than the claim (<span class="verse" data-ref="Acts 24:5" data-note="Paul slandered as a pestilent fellow.">Acts 24:5</span>).</li>
          <li><strong>Appeal to popularity:</strong> assuming many voices = truth (<span class="verse" data-ref="John 12:43" data-note="They loved the praise of men more than God.">John 12:43</span>).</li>
          <li><strong>Consistency &amp; non-contradiction:</strong> truth coheres because God is faithful (<span class="verse" data-ref="2 Timothy 3:16–17" data-note="Scripture grounds and corrects.">2 Timothy 3:16–17</span>).</li>
        </ul>
        <a class="chip" href="/israelite-research/media.html">Watch: Logic Tutorials</a>
      </section>

